content.description:
Pitch 1 - A short 30 foot handcrack in a block to a bolted anchor.

Pitch 2 - Climb the left-facing corner with fingers to tight-hands up through two roofs.
content.protection: (2) #.3 Camalots, (5) #.4 & #.5 Camalots, (3-4) #.75 Camalots, (2) #1 & #2 Camalots.
content.location:
To the right of

Power Play

and

Power Paws

.  Look for the obvious short first pitch and the fun-looking corner and roof.

content.description: This is the Unknown route 2 in Bloom's 2013 guidebook which is described as starting on a small ledge above a juniper. Starts on very thin hands and quickly transitions to fists and OW in a clean corner. At the end there is an awkward bulge which can be protected with a hand-sized piece at the back.
content.protection: single pieces from BD #0.75 to #3 for the start, then several pieces up to BD #6. No more than doubles in any size required. A VG9 works well near the top of the OW, but it is adequately protected with a #6. Save a hand-sized piece for the end. Nice bolt anchors with rap rings.
content.location: About 20' left of power line. Up a clean right-facing corner on top of blocks above a juniper.

content.description: In a left facing corner.  3rd route right of Power Line.  It is Splitter hands to big hands to a 2 bolt anchor.
content.protection: In Friends size (3) 3.0 and (4) 3.5.

content.description: Climb the flake crack up about 15 feet, then make an interesting boulder problem move to the right (crux) to gain a right-facing dihedral with a wavy wall on the right.  Climb the dihedral as it widens from tips to fists.
content.protection: (1) Black - Red Alien, (2) #.75 & #1 Camalots, (1) #2 - #3.5 Camalot.
content.location:
The route starts to the right of

Flower Power

and to the left of

Power Play

.

content.description: This route is just left of Batteries Not Included.  In the beginning you have some faceclimbing then up to some hard stemming.  It climbs along twin thin cracks.
content.protection: 2 Blue Aliens, 5 Green Aliens, 3 yellows Aliens and 1 1.5 friend

content.description: The pitch starts with .75 camalots to a ledge and then slowly tapers down from .5's to .3's and blue metolius at the top with a heartbreaker crux at the finish.
content.protection: Camalots: (1) #3, (1) #4, 4-5 greens, 4-5 purples, 4 greys, 3 blues (.3) and 2-3 blue metolius. There is a drilled angle near the top which I happily clipped. We used an 80 meter rope, a 70 may be just barely too short.
content.location: Head to the far right side of power wall. Go down a loose hill and pass an extremely splitter OW, continue around the corner from here and Ultimate Crack will be directly above you on top of a chossy looking pillar. Start with a scramble to the base of the crack and belay here. I found it easiest to go around the right side first and then around to the left near a chimney.

content.description: This is the route done to set up a TR on Powerline. Good fingers for the first fifty feet (mostly 5.11- finger locks to a short tips section) leads to a thin crux layback sequence at the top. Very fun!
content.protection: A .75 Camalot or two for the start and then many finger pieces down to a #0 TCU. The crux takes green aliens.

content.description:
Pitch 1: 90 feet, tips finger crack. Start on top of the big 12 foot block. The pitch has two distinct crux's, one at the start of the pitch off the block and the other below the large ledge. Line starts in small tips crack and arches gradually to the right before going straight up.

Pitch 2: 90 feet, tips crack. Belay from bolted anchors. Line starts just to the left of the anchors and has a high crux before the anchors.

Both pitches are sustained 5.12+ tips cracks.
content.protection:
Pitch 1: 9 Blue and 6 Grey Camalots.

Pitch 2: 3 Blue, 3 Gray and 2 Purple Camalots.

Draws for the anchors.
content.location: Show Us Your Tips is 30 yards left of Powerline, by a big 12 foot tall block with a squeeze chimney behind it.

content.description:
Sharp thin hands to hands corner in jet black varnish with a tips splitter just to the left. Nice warm up for the small-handed folks.

We top-roped around on the tips splitter and it's hard, maybe 12+, and feels kind of contrived as it's so close to the easier corner.
content.location: Left-facing corner left of the main zone at Power Wall.

content.description: Around the corner and to the right of Flower Power. It is the Twin Cracks that will get you pumped.  Ring locks come in handy here.
content.protection: .75 to 2 range more on the 1.5 Friends

content.description: The next crack to the right or Power Play.  this climb is short but pumpy.  Layback and jam the right facing flake.
content.protection: .75 to 2.5 in friends

content.description: Some say that it is the best 1" crack in the world.  And I am sure it is worth the little hike to it.  It is the 5th line to the left of Flower Power (which is the big left facing corner)
content.protection: Starts out .5 (purple BD) then gets into tight purples or orange metolius, then progresses to .4 grey BD and yellow Metolius towards the top.

content.description: Broken cracks in lighter rock to splitter fingers through a varnished bulge to shallow left-facing corner. Nice route but it's kind of out on its own and like many Power Wall routes it's a bit short.
content.location: This route is located on the far left side of Power Wall.

content.description:
Starts small. Gets big. Anchors up in the heavens.

Name is chiselled into the rock face. Super lame. Don't do that.
content.protection: Singles up to hands, then as many big cams as you need to feel comfy on 140 feet of 4-6 sized OW. Two bolts, but perhaps treat them as ornamental.

content.description: A steep zig-zagging .75 crack identifies the start of this route.  Some soft rock needs to be negotiated to get to the crack and then a deceivingly hard crux gives way to thin hands.  Save some finger pieces for the top.
content.protection: Camalots:(2).5, (4).75, (5)1.0 two bolt anchor at the top.
content.location: First route you come to when you walk around to the south facing side of the crag.

content.description: Sustained OW #4's, with at least 3 distinct cruxes.
content.protection: 6 #4 cams; 2# 3.5 cams (possible to substitute); 2 # 5's; 1#2 and 1 old #4.
content.location: Right side of the wall; just to the left of Electric (5.11+).

content.description: Flower Power is set in a left facing big corner on the Power Wall.  Hard to miss.  The crack is varied to small tips to start to good hand.  Pull through a small roof 1/2 way up (the crux) to the 2 bolt anchor.
content.protection: You will need two 60m ropes to do this.  We were able to do it with one 70m (be sure to tie a knot in the 70m).  Doubles on .5 to 3.5 maybe some extra on the .75.  You will need some long runners as well.

content.description: Bombay start to some hands fists and a nice stem box at the top On some really good stone
content.location: Left most route  but still on the main face and tucked  on the left side of a pillar a nice plaque at the base let's you know..

content.description: Right arching crack through a roof makes for a bouldery start.  Tapers down to tips by the time you reach the anchor.  Short but tough.  Don't grab the chains.  Clip off of that last hold.
content.protection: maybe a big piece for the start.  2 #2 camalot, 1 of everything smaller.  Maybe 2 .75 or .5 camalot too.  two bolt anchor.
content.location: Right of Power Line and Tips Lieback.

content.description: This unknown OW should be on the list of "must do" wide cracks in the creek! super splitter on black rock with crisp edges. my knee fit great most of the way. there is a small bulge 1/3 of the way up.  the cruxes are the slight flare down low and when it pinches down to old 4 camalots up high.  ends with hands and fingers! Awesome!
content.protection:
old camalots .3,(2)2,3.5,(2-3)4, (at least! 3)4.5,

an old 5 will fit but not necessary.

new 6 will fit in if you jam it in or; go in up high.

2 new 1/2 inch bolts with chains that are under the small roof.

you need a seventy meter rope!
content.location: the route is 15-20 ft right of "electric". it is the splitter that makes you say "damn!"

climbs.name: Apocalypso Variation (AKA Power, Hardly Know Her)

content.description:
This is a variation to the offwidth climb Apocalypso that was originally put up by Steve Quinlan and Les Hutchinson in 1987.

Pitch 1: The 30 foot hand crack is fun and easy. If you're doing Power, Hardly Know Her in one pitch it is recommended that you solo this pitch, or extend the heck out of your pieces. Please climb responsibly!

Pitch 2: Move right on the ledge and start up the obvious wide hands crack. Slowly move from hands to fists and navigate an awkward pod. The awkward pod turns back into hands and then do a creative move through a small fours roof. The original climb, Apocalypso (5.11) goes right from here up the slot and into the large corner. Power, Hardly Know Her, goes straight up the face into a BEAUTIFUL hands splitter. Follow this gorgeous wandering hands crack through all the hands sizes and then pull a funky little traverse move out left. Head back into the hands for a final and enjoyable stretch to the anchors.

The climb felt harder than 5.10 to me with my small hands, but the bigger handed folk I climbed with said it felt very comfortably 5.10. Bring more threes and fours if that size is hard for you!
content.protection: one .5 and some slings for the traverse. Three 1's. Lots of 2's and 3's. Two 4's. Bring extras in hand sizes that are hard for you.
content.location: Head to Power Wall and walk right until you reach the large detached pillar/ledge. Pitch 1 is hard to miss as the pretty little hands splitter.

content.description:
Short little twin crack/ left facing corner right of Batteries Not Included.

Good clean fun. Would be a classic if it were not over so quick.
content.protection: Hand sizes

content.description: Hands to some cups then some fists right in to a long stretch of big #4 camalots that gain some good ledges, and then some blue collar OW get you to the chains...
content.location: All the way around to the right... You can't miss this jem...
